# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mitochondrion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] **mitochondria**) is an organelle found in the cells of most eukaryotes, such as animals, plants and fungi.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria have a double membrane structure and use aerobic respiration to generate adenosine triphosphate (ATP), which is used throughout the cell as a source of chemical energy.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] They were discovered by Albert von Kölliker in 1857 in the voluntary muscles of insects.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The term *mitochondrion*, meaning "a thread-like granule", was coined by Carl Benda in 1898.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The mitochondrion is popularly nicknamed the "powerhouse of the cell", a phrase popularized by Philip Siekevitz in a 1957 *Scientific American* article of the same name.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria are commonly between 0.75 and 3 μm2 in cross section, but vary considerably in size and structure.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Unless specifically stained, they are not visible.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The mitochondrion is composed of compartments that carry out specialized functions.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These compartments or regions include the outer membrane, intermembrane space, inner membrane, cristae, and matrix.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In addition to supplying cellular energy, mitochondria are involved in other tasks, such as signaling, cellular differentiation, and cell death, as well as maintaining control of the cell cycle and cell growth.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial biogenesis is in turn temporally coordinated with these cellular processes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria are implicated in human disorders and conditions such as mitochondrial diseases, cardiac dysfunction, heart failure, and autism.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The number of mitochondria in a cell varies widely by organism, tissue, and cell type.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] A mature red blood cell has no mitochondria, whereas a liver cell can have more than 2000.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Although most of a eukaryotic cell's DNA is contained in the cell nucleus, the mitochondrion has its own genome ("mitogenome") that is similar to bacterial genomes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria may have a number of different shapes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] A mitochondrion contains outer and inner membranes composed of phospholipid bilayers and proteins.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The two membranes have different properties.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The matrix (space within the inner membrane), which is a fluid.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The inner membrane of mitochondria have folding to increase surface area, which in turn increases ATP (adenosine triphosphate) production.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria stripped of their outer membrane are called mitoplasts.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The **outer mitochondrial membrane**, which encloses the entire organelle, is 60 to 75 angstroms (Å) thick.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It has a protein-to-phospholipid ratio similar to that of the cell membrane (about 1:1 by weight).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It contains large numbers of integral membrane proteins called porins.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] A major trafficking protein is the pore-forming voltage-dependent anion channel (VDAC).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The VDAC is the primary transporter of nucleotides, ions and metabolites between the cytosol and the intermembrane space.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It is formed as a beta barrel that spans the outer membrane, similar to that in the gram-negative bacterial outer membrane.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Larger proteins can enter the mitochondrion if a signaling sequence at their N-terminus binds to a large multisubunit protein called translocase in the outer membrane, which then actively moves them across the membrane.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial pro-proteins are imported through specialised translocation complexes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The outer membrane also contains enzymes involved in activities such as the elongation of fatty acids, oxidation of epinephrine, and the degradation of tryptophan.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These enzymes include monoamine oxidase, rotenone-insensitive NADH-cytochrome c-reductase, kynurenine hydroxylase and fatty acid-CoA ligase.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Disruption of the outer membrane permits proteins in the intermembrane space to leak into the cytosol, leading to cell death.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The outer mitochondrial membrane can associate with the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) membrane, in a structure called MAM (mitochondria-associated ER-membrane).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This is important in the ER-mitochondria calcium signaling and is involved in the transfer of lipids between the ER and mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Outside the outer membrane are small (diameter: 60 Å) particles named sub-units of Parson.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The **mitochondrial intermembrane space** is the space between the outer membrane and the inner membrane.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It is also known as perimitochondrial space.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Because the outer membrane is freely permeable to small molecules, the concentrations of small molecules, such as ions and sugars, in the intermembrane space is the same as in the cytosol.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] However, large proteins must have a specific signaling sequence to be transported across the outer membrane, so the protein composition of this space is different from the protein composition of the cytosol.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] One protein that is localized to the intermembrane space in this way is cytochrome c.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It contains more than 151 different polypeptides, and has a very high protein-to-phospholipid ratio (more than 3:1 by weight, which is about 1 protein for 15 phospholipids).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The inner membrane is home to around 1/5 of the total protein in a mitochondrion.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Additionally, the inner membrane has an unusual lipid profile, being rich in cardiolipin.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This phospholipid was originally discovered in cow hearts in 1942, and is usually characteristic of mitochondrial and bacterial plasma membranes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Cardiolipin contains four fatty acids rather than two, and may help to make the inner membrane impermeable, and its disruption can lead to multiple clinical disorders including neurological disorders and cancer.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Unlike the outer membrane, the inner membrane does not contain porins, and is highly impermeable to all molecules.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Almost all ions and molecules require special membrane transporters to enter or exit the matrix.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Proteins are ferried into the matrix via the translocase of the inner membrane (TIM) complex or via OXA1L.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In addition, there is a membrane potential across the inner membrane, formed by the action of the enzymes of the electron transport chain.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Inner membrane fusion is mediated by the inner membrane protein OPA1.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The inner mitochondrial membrane is compartmentalized into numerous folds called cristae, which expand the surface area of the inner mitochondrial membrane, enhancing its ability to produce ATP.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] For typical liver mitochondria, the area of the inner membrane is about five times as large as that of the outer membrane.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This ratio is variable and mitochondria from cells that have a greater demand for ATP, such as muscle cells, contain even more cristae.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria within the same cell can have substantially different crista-density, with the ones that are required to produce more energy having much more crista-membrane surface.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These folds are studded with small round bodies known as F1 particles or oxysomes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The matrix is the space enclosed by the inner membrane.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It contains about 2/3 of the total proteins in a mitochondrion.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The matrix is important in the production of ATP with the aid of the ATP synthase contained in the inner membrane.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The matrix contains a highly concentrated mixture of hundreds of enzymes, special mitochondrial ribosomes, tRNA, and several copies of the mitochondrial DNA genome.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Of the enzymes, the major functions include oxidation of pyruvate and fatty acids, and the citric acid cycle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The DNA molecules are packaged into nucleoids by proteins, one of which is TFAM.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The most prominent roles of mitochondria are to produce the energy currency of the cell, ATP (i.e., phosphorylation of ADP), through respiration and to regulate cellular metabolism.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The central set of reactions involved in ATP production are collectively known as the citric acid cycle, or the Krebs cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] However, the mitochondrion has many other functions in addition to the production of ATP.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] A dominant role for the mitochondria is the production of ATP, as reflected by the large number of proteins in the inner membrane for this task.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This is done by oxidizing the major products of glucose: pyruvate, and NADH, which are produced in the cytosol.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This type of cellular respiration, known as aerobic respiration, is dependent on the presence of oxygen.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] When oxygen is limited, the glycolytic products will be metabolized by anaerobic fermentation, a process that is independent of the mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The production of ATP from glucose and oxygen has an approximately 13-times higher yield during aerobic respiration compared to fermentation.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Plant mitochondria can also produce a limited amount of ATP either by breaking the sugar produced during photosynthesis or without oxygen by using the alternate substrate nitrite.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] ATP crosses out through the inner membrane with the help of a specific protein, and across the outer membrane via porins.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] After conversion of ATP to ADP by dephosphorylation that releases energy, ADP returns via the same route.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This latter reaction "fills up" the amount of oxaloacetate in the citric acid cycle and is therefore an anaplerotic reaction, increasing the cycle's capacity to metabolize acetyl-CoA when the tissue's energy needs (e.g., in muscle) are suddenly increased by activity.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In the citric acid cycle, all the intermediates (e.g. citrate, iso-citrate, alpha-ketoglutarate, Succinyl-CoA, succinate, fumarate, malate and oxaloacetate) are regenerated during each turn of the cycle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Adding more of any of these intermediates to the mitochondrion therefore means that the additional amount is retained within the cycle, increasing all the other intermediates as one is converted into the other.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Hence, the addition of any one of them to the cycle has an anaplerotic effect, and its removal has a cataplerotic effect.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These anaplerotic and cataplerotic reactions will, during the course of the cycle, increase or decrease the amount of oxaloacetate available to combine with acetyl-CoA to form citric acid.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This in turn increases or decreases the rate of ATP production by the mitochondrion, and thus the availability of ATP to the cell.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Acetyl-CoA, on the other hand, derived from pyruvate oxidation, or from the beta-oxidation of fatty acids, is the only fuel to enter the citric acid cycle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] With each turn of the cycle one molecule of acetyl-CoA is consumed for every molecule of oxaloacetate present in the mitochondrial matrix, and is never regenerated.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It is the oxidation of the acetate portion of acetyl-CoA that produces CO2 and water, with the energy thus released captured in the form of ATP.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In the liver, the carboxylation of cytosolic pyruvate into intra-mitochondrial oxaloacetate is an early step in the gluconeogenic pathway, which converts lactate and de-aminated alanine into glucose, under the influence of high levels of glucagon and/or epinephrine in the blood.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The enzymes of the citric acid cycle are located in the mitochondrial matrix, with the exception of succinate dehydrogenase, which is bound to the inner mitochondrial membrane as part of Complex II.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The citric acid cycle oxidizes the acetyl-CoA to carbon dioxide, and, in the process, produces reduced cofactors (three molecules of NADH and one molecule of FADH2) that are a source of electrons for the electron transport chain, and a molecule of GTP (which is readily converted to an ATP).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The electrons from NADH and FADH2 are transferred between multiple coenzymes, and ultimately to oxygen (O2) in several steps via the electron transport chain.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] NADH and FADH2 molecules are produced within the matrix via the citric acid cycle and in the cytoplasm by glycolysis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Reducing equivalents from the cytoplasm can be imported via the malate-aspartate shuttle system of antiporter proteins or fed into the electron transport chain using a glycerol phosphate shuttle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The major energy-releasing reactions that make the mitochondrion the "powerhouse of the cell" occur at protein complexes I, III and IV in the inner mitochondrial membrane (NADH dehydrogenase (ubiquinone), cytochrome c reductase, and cytochrome c oxidase).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] releasing a lot of free energy from the reactants without breaking bonds of an organic fuel.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] While the reactions are controlled by an electron transport chain, free electrons are not amongst the reactants or products in the three reactions shown and therefore do not affect the free energy released, which is used to pump protons (H+) into the intermembrane space.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This process is efficient, but a small percentage of electrons may prematurely reduce oxygen, forming reactive oxygen species such as superoxide.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This can cause oxidative stress in the mitochondria and may contribute to the decline in mitochondrial function associated with aging.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] As the proton concentration increases in the intermembrane space, a strong electrochemical gradient is established across the inner membrane.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The protons can return to the matrix through the ATP synthase complex, and their potential energy is used to synthesize ATP from ADP and inorganic phosphate (Pi).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This process is called chemiosmosis, and was first described by Peter Mitchell, who was awarded the 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his work.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Later, part of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Paul D.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Walker for their clarification of the working mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Under certain conditions, protons can re-enter the mitochondrial matrix without contributing to ATP synthesis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This process is known as *proton leak* or mitochondrial uncoupling and is due to the facilitated diffusion of protons into the matrix.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The process results in the unharnessed potential energy of the proton electrochemical gradient being released as heat.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The process is mediated by a proton channel called thermogenin, or UCP1.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Thermogenin is primarily found in brown adipose tissue, or brown fat, and is responsible for non-shivering thermogenesis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Brown adipose tissue is found in mammals, and is at its highest levels in early life and in hibernating animals.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In humans, brown adipose tissue is present at birth and decreases with age.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Due to heat production, some studies suggested that mitochondria run at a higher temperature.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The internal temperature in mitochondria was previously estimated to be 10C higher than the cytoplasm.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] However, the theory of this remains controversial and disputed as an issue with the sensor, and that temperatures this high would cause damage to mitochondrial components.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial fatty acid synthesis (mtFAS) is essential for cellular respiration and mitochondrial biogenesis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In response to mitochondrial acetyl-CoA availability, mtFAS builds acyl chains on the 4'-phosphopantetheine group of the matrix-soluble scaffold protein ACP (holo-ACP), producing acyl-ACP species with varying chain lengths of at least eight carbons.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Among these, octanoyl-ACP (C8) serves as the precursor for lipoic acid biosynthesis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In contrast, longer-chain acyl-ACPs (C12–C18) allosterically activate the network of LYRM proteins, which comprises at least 12 members in humans and regulates mitochondrial translation, iron-sulfur cluster biogenesis, and the assembly of electron transport chain complexes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] MtFAS and ACP thus coordinate the activation of mitochondrial respiration in response to substrate availability.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This enables cells to increase their oxidative capacity when substrates are abundant and prevents the electron transport chain from running empty and inducing the formation of reactive oxygen species (ROS) under substrate-limited conditions.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] MtFAS is also thought to play a role as a mediator in intracellular signaling due to its influence on the levels of bioactive lipids, such as lysophospholipids and sphingolipids.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The concentrations of free calcium in the cell can regulate an array of reactions and is important for signal transduction in the cell.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria can transiently store calcium, a contributing process for the cell's homeostasis of calcium.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Their ability to rapidly take in calcium for later release makes them good "cytosolic buffers" for calcium.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The endoplasmic reticulum (ER) is the most significant storage site of calcium, and there is a significant interplay between the mitochondrion and ER with regard to calcium.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The calcium is taken up into the matrix by the mitochondrial calcium uniporter on the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It is primarily driven by the mitochondrial membrane potential.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Release of this calcium back into the cell's interior can occur via a sodium-calcium exchange protein or via "calcium-induced-calcium-release" pathways.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This can initiate calcium spikes or calcium waves with large changes in the membrane potential.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These can activate a series of second messenger system proteins that can coordinate processes such as neurotransmitter release in nerve cells and release of hormones in endocrine cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Ca2+ influx to the mitochondrial matrix has recently been implicated as a mechanism to regulate respiratory bioenergetics by allowing the electrochemical potential across the membrane to transiently "pulse" from ΔΨ-dominated to pH-dominated, facilitating a reduction of oxidative stress.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In neurons, concomitant increases in cytosolic and mitochondrial calcium act to synchronize neuronal activity with mitochondrial energy metabolism.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial matrix calcium levels can reach the tens of micromolar levels, which is necessary for the activation of isocitrate dehydrogenase, one of the key regulatory enzymes of the Krebs cycle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The relationship between cellular proliferation and mitochondria has been investigated.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Tumor cells require ample ATP to synthesize bioactive compounds such as lipids, proteins, and nucleotides for rapid proliferation.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The majority of ATP in tumor cells is generated via the oxidative phosphorylation pathway (OxPhos).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Interference with OxPhos cause cell cycle arrest suggesting that mitochondria play a role in cell proliferation.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial ATP production is also vital for cell division and differentiation in infection in addition to basic functions in the cell including the regulation of cell volume, solute concentration, and cellular architecture.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] ATP levels differ at various stages of the cell cycle suggesting that there is a relationship between the abundance of ATP and the cell's ability to enter a new cell cycle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] ATP's role in the basic functions of the cell make the cell cycle sensitive to changes in the availability of mitochondrial derived ATP.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The variation in ATP levels at different stages of the cell cycle support the hypothesis that mitochondria play an important role in cell cycle regulation.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Although the specific mechanisms between mitochondria and the cell cycle regulation is not well understood, studies have shown that low energy cell cycle checkpoints monitor the energy capability before committing to another round of cell division.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Programmed cell death (PCD) is crucial for various physiological functions, including organ development and cellular homeostasis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It serves as an intrinsic mechanism to prevent malignant transformation and plays a fundamental role in immunity by aiding in antiviral defense, pathogen elimination, inflammation, and immune cell recruitment.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria have long been recognized for their central role in the intrinsic pathway of apoptosis, a form of PCD.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In recent decades, they have also been identified as a signalling hub for much of the innate immune system.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The endosymbiotic origin of mitochondria distinguishes them from other cellular components, and the exposure of mitochondrial elements to the cytosol can trigger the same pathways as infection markers.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These pathways lead to apoptosis, autophagy, or the induction of proinflammatory genes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria contribute to apoptosis by releasing cytochrome *c*, which directly induces the formation of apoptosomes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Additionally, they are a source of various damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These DAMPs are often recognised by the same pattern-recognition receptors (PRRs) that respond to pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) during infections.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] For example, mitochondrial mtDNA resembles bacterial DNA due to its lack of CpG methylation and can be detected by Toll-like receptor 9 and cGAS.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Double-stranded RNA (dsRNA), produced due to bidirectional mitochondrial transcription, can activate viral sensing pathways through RIG-I-like receptors.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Additionally, the *N*-formylation of mitochondrial proteins, similar to that of bacterial proteins, can be recognized by formyl peptide receptors.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Normally, these mitochondrial components are sequestered from the rest of the cell but are released following mitochondrial membrane permeabilization during apoptosis or passively after mitochondrial damage.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] However, mitochondria also play an active role in innate immunity, releasing mtDNA in response to metabolic cues.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria are also the localization site for immune and apoptosis regulatory proteins, such as BAX, MAVS (located on the outer membrane), and NLRX1 (found in the matrix).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These proteins are modulated by the mitochondrial metabolic status and mitochondrial dynamics.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Some cells "donate" mitochondria to other cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Such donations occur in multiple cell types, in organisms such as yeast, molluscs, and rodents.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial donation was first observed in 2006.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] As of 2025, it had not been observed in humans *in vivo*.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Donations may occur to help damaged cells, trigger tissue repair or the immune system, or to power distressed cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Researchers cultured human mitochondria-free lung cancer cells with stem cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The stem cells ejected mitochondria, which were absorbed by the lung cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The lung cells then recovered their ability to divide and metabolize glucose.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria were then detected moving among lung, heart, brain, fat, bone, and other cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Research has not identified how a cell indicates that it needs mitochondrial assistance or how other cells read those indicators.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Various purposes have been observed to explain such donations.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Some mitochondrial functions are performed only in specific types of cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] For example, mitochondria in liver cells contain enzymes that allow them to detoxify ammonia, a waste product of protein metabolism.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] A mutation in the genes regulating any of these functions can result in mitochondrial diseases.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial proteins, including those produced from mitochondrial DNA and those imported from the cytoplasm, vary depending on the tissue and the species.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In humans, 615 distinct types of proteins have been identified from cardiac mitochondria, whereas in rats, 940 proteins have been reported.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The mitochondrial proteome is thought to be dynamically regulated.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Not every function of the mitochondrion is universally conserved in every organism that has it, but some are more commonly kept than the others.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Most make ATP in some way (the vast majority by oxidative phosphorylation; a minority called hydrogenosomes instead use a hydrogenase).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] All known versions perform iron–sulphur cluster biosynthesis: this is made especially clear by the mitosome, which retains *only* this function.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Also universally kept is the machinery for importing proteins from the cytoplasm into the mitochondrion, without which the mitochondrion cannot function at all.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria (or related structures) are found in all eukaryotes (except the Oxymonad *Monocercomonoides*).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Although commonly depicted as bean-like structures they form a highly dynamic network in the majority of cells where they constantly undergo fission and fusion.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The population of all the mitochondria of a given cell constitutes the **chondriome**.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria vary in number and location according to cell type.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] A single mitochondrion is often found in unicellular organisms, while human liver cells have about 1000–2000 mitochondria per cell, making up 1/5 of the cell volume.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The mitochondrial content of otherwise similar cells can vary substantially in size and membrane potential, with differences arising from sources including uneven partitioning at cell division, leading to extrinsic differences in ATP levels and downstream cellular processes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The mitochondria can be found nestled between myofibrils of muscle or wrapped around the sperm flagellum.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Often, they form a complex 3D branching network inside the cell with the cytoskeleton.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The association with the cytoskeleton determines mitochondrial shape, which can affect the function as well: different structures of the mitochondrial network may afford the population a variety of physical, chemical, and signalling advantages or disadvantages.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondria in cells are always distributed along microtubules and the distribution of these organelles is also correlated with the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Recent evidence suggests that vimentin, one of the components of the cytoskeleton, is also critical to the association with the cytoskeleton.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Changes in mitochondrial number, structure, and activity accompany shifts in cellular state and environmental conditions.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In many stem and progenitor cells, differentiation is associated with increased mitochondrial content and greater reliance on oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Reprogramming differentiated cells into induced pluripotent stem cells generally produces the opposite pattern, with increased reliance on glycolysis and a less developed mitochondrial network.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial metabolism and signaling also influence the activation, differentiation, and function of immune cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial networks are continually altered through fission, fusion, mitophagy, and intracellular transport.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These processes affect mitochondrial distribution, quality control, metabolism, signaling, and cellular responses to stress.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Abnormal mitochondrial dynamics have been associated with metabolic, cardiovascular, neurodegenerative, and neoplastic diseases.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The mitochondria-associated ER membrane (MAM) is another structural element that is increasingly recognized for its critical role in cellular physiology and homeostasis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Once considered a technical snag in cell fractionation techniques, the alleged ER vesicle contaminants that invariably appeared in the mitochondrial fraction have been re-identified as membranous structures derived from the MAM—the interface between mitochondria and the ER.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Physical coupling between these two organelles had previously been observed in electron micrographs and has more recently been probed with fluorescence microscopy.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Such studies estimate that at the MAM, which may comprise up to 20% of the mitochondrial outer membrane, the ER and mitochondria are separated by a mere 10–25 nm and held together by protein tethering complexes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Purified MAM from subcellular fractionation is enriched in enzymes involved in phospholipid exchange, in addition to channels associated with Ca2+ signaling.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These hints of a prominent role for the MAM in the regulation of cellular lipid stores and signal transduction have been borne out, with significant implications for mitochondrial-associated cellular phenomena, as discussed below.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Not only has the MAM provided insight into the mechanistic basis underlying such physiological processes as intrinsic apoptosis and the propagation of calcium signaling, but it also favors a more refined view of the mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The MAM is enriched in enzymes involved in lipid biosynthesis, such as phosphatidylserine synthase on the ER face and phosphatidylserine decarboxylase on the mitochondrial face.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Because mitochondria are dynamic organelles constantly undergoing fission and fusion events, they require a constant and well-regulated supply of phospholipids for membrane integrity.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Such trafficking capacity depends on the MAM, which has been shown to facilitate transfer of lipid intermediates between organelles.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In contrast to the standard vesicular mechanism of lipid transfer, evidence indicates that the physical proximity of the ER and mitochondrial membranes at the MAM allows for lipid flipping between opposed bilayers.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Despite this unusual and seemingly energetically unfavorable mechanism, such transport does not require ATP.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The MAM may also be part of the secretory pathway, in addition to its role in intracellular lipid trafficking.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In particular, the MAM appears to be an intermediate destination between the rough ER and the Golgi in the pathway that leads to very-low-density lipoprotein, or VLDL, assembly and secretion.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The MAM thus serves as a critical metabolic and trafficking hub in lipid metabolism.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] But the presence of the MAM resolves this apparent contradiction: the close physical association between the two organelles results in Ca2+ microdomains at contact points that facilitate efficient Ca2+ transmission from the ER to the mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Transmission occurs in response to so-called "Ca2+ puffs" generated by spontaneous clustering and activation of IP3R, a canonical ER membrane Ca2+ channel.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The fate of these puffs—in particular, whether they remain restricted to isolated locales or integrated into Ca2+ waves for propagation throughout the cell—is determined in large part by MAM dynamics.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This Ca2+ tunneling occurs through the low-affinity Ca2+ receptor VDAC1, which recently has been shown to be physically tethered to the IP3R clusters on the ER membrane and enriched at the MAM.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The ability of mitochondria to serve as a Ca2+ sink is a result of the electrochemical gradient generated during oxidative phosphorylation, which makes tunneling of the cation an exergonic process.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Normal, mild calcium influx from cytosol into the mitochondrial matrix causes transient depolarization that is corrected by pumping out protons.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] But transmission of Ca2+ is not unidirectional; rather, it is a two-way street.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The properties of the Ca2+ pump SERCA and the channel IP3R present on the ER membrane facilitate feedback regulation coordinated by MAM function.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In particular, the clearance of Ca2+ by the MAM allows for spatio-temporal patterning of Ca2+ signaling because Ca2+ alters IP3R activity in a biphasic manner.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] SERCA is likewise affected by mitochondrial feedback: uptake of Ca2+ by the MAM stimulates ATP production, thus providing energy that enables SERCA to reload the ER with Ca2+ for continued Ca2+ efflux at the MAM.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Thus, the MAM is not a passive buffer for Ca2+ puffs; rather it helps modulate further Ca2+ signaling through feedback loops that affect ER dynamics.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Regulating ER release of Ca2+ at the MAM is especially critical because only a certain window of Ca2+ uptake sustains the mitochondria, and consequently the cell, at homeostasis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Sufficient intraorganelle Ca2+ signaling is required to stimulate metabolism by activating dehydrogenase enzymes critical to flux through the citric acid cycle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] However, once Ca2+ signaling in the mitochondria passes a certain threshold, it stimulates the intrinsic pathway of apoptosis in part by collapsing the mitochondrial membrane potential required for metabolism.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Given the need for such fine regulation of Ca2+ signaling, it is perhaps unsurprising that dysregulated mitochondrial Ca2+ has been implicated in several neurodegenerative diseases, while the catalogue of tumor suppressors includes a few that are enriched at the MAM.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Recent advances in the identification of the tethers between the mitochondrial and ER membranes suggest that the scaffolding function of the molecular elements involved is secondary to other, non-structural functions.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In yeast, ERMES, a multiprotein complex of interacting ER- and mitochondrial-resident membrane proteins, is required for lipid transfer at the MAM and exemplifies this principle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] One of its components, for example, is also a constituent of the protein complex required for insertion of transmembrane beta-barrel proteins into the lipid bilayer.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] However, a homologue of the ERMES complex has not yet been identified in mammalian cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Glucose-related protein 75 (grp75) is another dual-function protein.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In addition to the matrix pool of grp75, a portion serves as a chaperone that physically links the mitochondrial and ER Ca2+ channels VDAC and IP3R for efficient Ca2+ transmission at the MAM.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Another potential tether is Sigma-1R, a non-opioid receptor whose stabilization of ER-resident IP3R may preserve communication at the MAM during the metabolic stress response.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The MAM is a critical signaling, metabolic, and trafficking hub in the cell that allows for the integration of ER and mitochondrial physiology.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Coupling between these organelles is not simply structural but functional as well and critical for overall cellular physiology and homeostasis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The MAM thus offers a perspective on mitochondria that diverges from the traditional view of this organelle as a static, isolated unit appropriated for its metabolic capacity by the cell.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Instead, this mitochondrial-ER interface emphasizes the integration of the mitochondria, the product of an endosymbiotic event, into diverse cellular processes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Recently it has also been shown, that mitochondria and MAM-s in neurons are anchored to specialised intercellular communication sites (so called somatic-junctions).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Microglial processes monitor and protect neuronal functions at these sites, and MAM-s are supposed to have an important role in this type of cellular quality-control.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] There are two hypotheses about the origin of mitochondria: endosymbiotic and autogenous.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The endosymbiotic hypothesis suggests that mitochondria were originally prokaryotic cells, capable of implementing oxidative mechanisms that were not possible for eukaryotic cells; they became endosymbionts living inside the eukaryote.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In the autogenous hypothesis, mitochondria were born by splitting off a portion of DNA from the nucleus of the eukaryotic cell at the time of divergence with the prokaryotes; this DNA portion would have been enclosed by membranes, which could not be crossed by proteins.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Since mitochondria have many features in common with bacteria, the endosymbiotic hypothesis is the more widely accepted of the two accounts.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] A mitochondrion contains DNA, which is organized as several copies of a single, usually circular chromosome.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This mitochondrial chromosome contains genes for redox proteins, such as those of the respiratory chain.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The CoRR hypothesis proposes that this co-location is required for redox regulation.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The mitochondrial genome codes for some RNAs of ribosomes, and the 22 tRNAs necessary for the translation of mRNAs into protein.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The circular structure is also found in prokaryotes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The proto-mitochondrion was probably closely related to the order *Rickettsiales*, which is in class Alphaproteobacteria of phylum Pseudomonadota.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] However, the exact relationship of the ancestor of mitochondria to the alphaproteobacteria and whether the mitochondrion was formed at the same time or after the nucleus, remains controversial.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] For example, it has been suggested that the SAR11 clade of bacteria shares a relatively recent common ancestor with the mitochondria, while phylogenomic analyses indicate that mitochondria evolved from a Pseudomonadota lineage that is closely related to or a member of alphaproteobacteria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Some papers describe mitochondria as sister to the alphaproteobacteria, together forming the sister to the marineproteo1 group, together forming the sister to Magnetococcidae.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The ribosomes coded for by the mitochondrial DNA are similar to those from bacteria in size and structure.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] They closely resemble the bacterial 70S ribosome and not the 80S cytoplasmic ribosomes, which are coded for by nuclear DNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The endosymbiotic relationship of mitochondria with their host cells was popularized by Lynn Margulis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The endosymbiotic theory suggests that mitochondria descended from aerobic bacteria that somehow survived endocytosis by another cell, and became incorporated into the cytoplasm.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The ability of these bacteria to conduct respiration in host cells that had relied on glycolysis and fermentation would have provided a considerable evolutionary advantage.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] This symbiotic relationship probably developed 1.7 to 2 billion years ago.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] A few groups of unicellular eukaryotes have only vestigial mitochondria or derived structures: the microsporidians, metamonads, and archamoebae.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] These groups appear as the most primitive eukaryotes on phylogenetic trees constructed using rRNA information, which once suggested that they appeared before the origin of mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] However, this is now known to be an artifact of *long-branch attraction*: They are derived groups and retain genes or organelles derived from mitochondria (e. g., mitosomes and hydrogenosomes).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Hydrogenosomes, mitosomes, and related organelles as found in some loricifera (e. g.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] *Henneguya zschokkei*) are together classified as MROs, mitochondrion-related organelles.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Eukaryotes with less conventional life habits, especially anaerobes and parasitic species, tend to have vastly reduced versions of the mitochondrion because many features are simply useless to their lifestyle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] In more stiking cases of reduction, "core" features such as electron transport chain, oxidative phosphorylation, even ATP production can be dispensed of.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Mitochondrial proteins responsible for these functions, whether originally found in mtDNA or the nucleus, is simply lost.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Some also have lost mitochondrial DNA altogether.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Having separately occurred in many lineages to different degrees, these changes exemplify convergent evolution.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The Alveolata includes many parasitic species, some with no mitochondrial DNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Even in a typical photosynthetic free-living organism of the group (*Chromera*), the mitochondrion has lost oxidative phosphorylation complexes I and III completely.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Its mtDNA only has three genes, *cox1*, *cox3*, and a rRNA fragment.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The parasite *Cryptosporidium* has no mitochondrial DNA, with what little functions it performs presumably transferred to the nucleus.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] It has an altered ATP generation system that renders the parasite resistant to many classical mitochondrial inhibitors such as cyanide, azide, and atovaquone.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] *Amoebophrya cerati*, a marine parasitic dinoflagellate (a kind of alveolate), also has no mitochondrial DNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Using *Chomera* as a reference, it has moved *cox1* to the nuclear genome and lost the two other genes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The hydrogenosomes, mitochondrion derivatives that has lost all OXPHOS ability and instead uses a newly acquired hydrogenase to make ATP, also largely lack DNA save for some transitional examples.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] The mitosomes, which does not make any energy at all and is presumably only kept for the ability to make iron-sulfur clusters, have no DNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p01] Both terms are merely *descriptive* terms based on the functions of the organelles and both have eolved more than just once.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The human mitochondrial genome is a circular double-stranded DNA molecule of about 16 kilobases.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] It encodes 37 genes: 13 for subunits of respiratory complexes I, III, IV and V, 22 for mitochondrial tRNA (for the 20 standard amino acids, plus an extra gene for leucine and serine), and 2 for rRNA (12S and 16S rRNA).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] One mitochondrion can contain two to ten copies of its DNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] One of the two mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) strands has a disproportionately higher ratio of the heavier nucleotides adenine and guanine, and this is termed the heavy strand (or H strand), whereas the other strand is termed the light strand (or L strand).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The origin of replication for the L strand (OriL) is localized on the H strand 11,000 bp downstream of OriH, located within a cluster of genes coding for tRNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] As in prokaryotes, there is a very high proportion of coding DNA and an absence of repeats.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Mitochondrial genes are transcribed as multigenic transcripts, which are cleaved and polyadenylated to yield mature mRNAs.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Most proteins necessary for mitochondrial function are encoded by genes in the cell nucleus and the corresponding proteins are imported into the mitochondrion.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The exact number of genes encoded by the nucleus and the mitochondrial genome differs between species.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Most mitochondrial genomes are circular.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In general, mitochondrial DNA lacks introns, as is the case in the human mitochondrial genome; however, introns have been observed in some eukaryotic mitochondrial DNA, such as that of yeast and protists, including *Dictyostelium discoideum*.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Between protein-coding regions, tRNAs are present.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Mitochondrial tRNA genes have different sequences from the nuclear tRNAs, but lookalikes of mitochondrial tRNAs have been found in the nuclear chromosomes with high sequence similarity.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In animals, the mitochondrial genome is typically a single circular chromosome that is approximately 16 kb long and has 37 genes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The genes, while highly conserved, may vary in location.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Curiously, this pattern is not found in the human body louse (*Pediculus humanus*).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Instead, this mitochondrial genome is arranged in 18 minicircular chromosomes, each of which is 3–4 kb long and has one to three genes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This pattern is also found in other sucking lice, but not in chewing lice.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Recombination has been shown to occur between the minichromosomes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The near-absence of genetic recombination in mitochondrial DNA makes it a useful source of information for studying population genetics and evolutionary biology.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Because all the mitochondrial DNA is inherited as a single unit, or haplotype, the relationships between mitochondrial DNA from different individuals can be represented as a gene tree.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Patterns in these gene trees can be used to infer the evolutionary history of populations.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The classic example of this is in human evolutionary genetics, where the molecular clock can be used to provide a recent date for mitochondrial Eve.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This is often interpreted as strong support for a recent modern human expansion out of Africa.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Another human example is the sequencing of mitochondrial DNA from Neanderthal bones.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The relatively large evolutionary distance between the mitochondrial DNA sequences of Neanderthals and living humans has been interpreted as evidence for the lack of interbreeding between Neanderthals and modern humans.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] However, mitochondrial DNA reflects only the history of the females in a population.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This can be partially overcome by the use of paternal genetic sequences, such as the non-recombining region of the Y-chromosome.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Recent measurements of the molecular clock for mitochondrial DNA reported a value of 1 mutation every 7884 years dating back to the most recent common ancestor of humans and apes, which is consistent with estimates of mutation rates of autosomal DNA (10−8 per base per generation).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] While slight variations on the standard genetic code had been predicted earlier, none was discovered until 1979, when researchers studying human mitochondrial genes determined that they used an alternative code.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Nonetheless, the mitochondria of many other eukaryotes, including most plants, use the standard code.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Many slight variants have been discovered since, including various alternative mitochondrial codes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Further, the AUA, AUC, and AUU codons are all allowable start codons.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Some of these differences should be regarded as pseudo-changes in the genetic code due to the phenomenon of RNA editing, which is common in mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In higher plants, it was thought that CGG encoded for tryptophan and not arginine; however, the codon in the processed RNA was discovered to be the UGG codon, consistent with the standard genetic code for tryptophan.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Of note, the arthropod mitochondrial genetic code has undergone parallel evolution within a phylum, with some organisms uniquely translating AGG to lysine.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Mitochondria divide by mitochondrial fission, a form of binary fission that is also done by bacteria although the process is tightly regulated by the host eukaryotic cell and involves communication between and contact with several other organelles.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The regulation of this division differs between eukaryotes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In many single-celled eukaryotes, their growth and division are linked to the cell cycle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] For example, a single mitochondrion may divide synchronously with the nucleus.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This division and segregation process must be tightly controlled so that each daughter cell receives at least one mitochondrion.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In other eukaryotes (in mammals for example), mitochondria may replicate their DNA and divide mainly in response to the energy needs of the cell, rather than in phase with the cell cycle.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] When the energy needs of a cell are high, mitochondria grow and divide.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] When energy use is low, mitochondria are destroyed or become inactive.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In such examples mitochondria are apparently randomly distributed to the daughter cells during the division of the cytoplasm.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Mitochondrial dynamics, the balance between mitochondrial fusion and fission, is an important factor in pathologies associated with several disease conditions.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The hypothesis of mitochondrial binary fission has relied on the visualization by fluorescence microscopy and conventional transmission electron microscopy (TEM).
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The resolution of fluorescence microscopy (≈200 nm) is insufficient to distinguish structural details, such as double mitochondrial membrane in mitochondrial division or even to distinguish individual mitochondria when several are close together.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Conventional TEM has also some technical limitations in verifying mitochondrial division.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Cryo-electron tomography was recently used to visualize mitochondrial division in frozen hydrated intact cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] It revealed that mitochondria divide by budding.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] An individual's mitochondrial genes are inherited only from the mother, with rare exceptions.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In humans, when an egg cell is fertilized by a sperm, the mitochondria, and therefore the mitochondrial DNA, usually come from the egg only.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The sperm's mitochondria enter the egg, but do not contribute genetic information to the embryo.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Instead, paternal mitochondria are marked with ubiquitin to select them for later destruction inside the embryo.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The egg cell contains relatively few mitochondria, but these mitochondria divide to populate the cells of the adult organism.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This mode is seen in most organisms, including the majority of animals.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] However, mitochondria in some species can sometimes be inherited paternally.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This is the norm among certain coniferous plants, although not in pine trees and yews.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] For Mytilids, paternal inheritance only occurs within males of the species.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] It has been suggested that it occurs at a very low level in humans.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Uniparental inheritance leads to little opportunity for genetic recombination between different lineages of mitochondria, although a single mitochondrion can contain 2–10 copies of its DNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] What recombination does take place maintains genetic integrity rather than maintaining diversity.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] However, there are studies showing evidence of recombination in mitochondrial DNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] It is clear that the enzymes necessary for recombination are present in mammalian cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Further, evidence suggests that animal mitochondria can undergo recombination.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The data are more controversial in humans, although indirect evidence of recombination exists.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Entities undergoing uniparental inheritance and with little to no recombination may be expected to be subject to Muller's ratchet, the accumulation of deleterious mutations until functionality is lost.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Animal populations of mitochondria avoid this buildup through a developmental process known as the mtDNA bottleneck.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The bottleneck exploits stochastic processes in the cell to increase the cell-to-cell variability in mutant load as an organism develops: a single egg cell with some proportion of mutant mtDNA thus produces an embryo where different cells have different mutant loads.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Cell-level selection may then act to remove those cells with more mutant mtDNA, leading to a stabilization or reduction in mutant load between generations.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The mechanism underlying the bottleneck is debated, with a recent mathematical and experimental metastudy providing evidence for a combination of random partitioning of mtDNAs at cell divisions and random turnover of mtDNA molecules within the cell.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Mitochondria can repair oxidative DNA damage by mechanisms analogous to those occurring in the cell nucleus.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The proteins employed in mtDNA repair are encoded by nuclear genes, and are translocated to the mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The DNA repair pathways in mammalian mitochondria include base excision repair, double-strand break repair, direct reversal and mismatch repair.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Alternatively, DNA damage may be bypassed, rather than repaired, by translesion synthesis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Of the several DNA repair process in mitochondria, the base excision repair pathway has been most comprehensively studied.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Base excision repair is carried out by a sequence of enzyme-catalyzed steps that include recognition and excision of a damaged DNA base, removal of the resulting abasic site, end processing, gap filling and ligation.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] A common damage in mtDNA that is repaired by base excision repair is 8-oxoguanine produced by oxidation of guanine.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Double-strand breaks can be repaired by homologous recombinational repair in both mammalian mtDNA and plant mtDNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Double-strand breaks in mtDNA can also be repaired by microhomology-mediated end joining.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Although there is evidence for the repair processes of direct reversal and mismatch repair in mtDNA, these processes are not well characterized.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Damage and subsequent dysfunction in mitochondria is an important factor in a range of human diseases due to their influence in cell metabolism.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Mitochondrial disorders often present as neurological disorders, including autism.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] They can also manifest as myopathy, diabetes, multiple endocrinopathy, and a variety of other systemic disorders.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Diseases caused by mutation in the mtDNA include Kearns–Sayre syndrome, MELAS syndrome and Leber's hereditary optic neuropathy.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In the vast majority of cases, these diseases are transmitted by a female to her children, as the zygote derives its mitochondria and hence its mtDNA from the ovum.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] It has also been reported that drug tolerant cancer cells have an increased number and size of mitochondria which suggested an increase in mitochondrial biogenesis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] A 2022 study in *Nature Nanotechnology* has reported that cancer cells can hijack the mitochondria from immune cells via physical tunneling nanotubes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In other diseases, defects in nuclear genes lead to dysfunction of mitochondrial proteins.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This is the case in Friedreich's ataxia, hereditary spastic paraplegia, and Wilson's disease.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] These diseases are inherited in a dominance relationship, as applies to most other genetic diseases.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] A variety of disorders can be caused by nuclear mutations of oxidative phosphorylation enzymes, such as coenzyme Q10 deficiency and Barth syndrome.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Environmental influences may interact with hereditary predispositions and cause mitochondrial disease.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] For example, there may be a link between pesticide exposure and the later onset of Parkinson's disease.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Mitochondria-mediated oxidative stress plays a role in cardiomyopathy in type 2 diabetics.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Increased fatty acid delivery to the heart increases fatty acid uptake by cardiomyocytes, resulting in increased fatty acid oxidation in these cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This process increases the reducing equivalents available to the electron transport chain of the mitochondria, ultimately increasing reactive oxygen species (ROS) production.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] ROS increases uncoupling proteins (UCPs) and potentiate proton leakage through the adenine nucleotide translocator (ANT), the combination of which uncouples the mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Uncoupling then increases oxygen consumption by the mitochondria, compounding the increase in fatty acid oxidation.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This creates a vicious cycle of uncoupling; furthermore, even though oxygen consumption increases, ATP synthesis does not increase proportionally because the mitochondria are uncoupled.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Less ATP availability ultimately results in an energy deficit presenting as reduced cardiac efficiency and contractile dysfunction.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] To compound the problem, impaired sarcoplasmic reticulum calcium release and reduced mitochondrial reuptake limits peak cytosolic levels of the important signaling ion during muscle contraction.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Decreased intra-mitochondrial calcium concentration increases dehydrogenase activation and ATP synthesis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] So in addition to lower ATP synthesis due to fatty acid oxidation, ATP synthesis is impaired by poor calcium signaling as well, causing cardiac problems for diabetics.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Mitochondria also modulate processes such as testicular somatic cell development, spermatogonial stem cell differentiation, luminal acidification, testosterone production in testes, and more.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Thus, dysfunction of mitochondria in spermatozoa can be a cause for infertility.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In efforts to combat mitochondrial disease, mitochondrial replacement therapy (MRT) has been developed.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This form of in vitro fertilization uses donor mitochondria, which avoids the transmission of diseases caused by mutations of mitochondrial DNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] However, this therapy is still being researched and can introduce genetic modification, as well as safety concerns.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] These diseases are rare but can be extremely debilitating and progressive diseases, thus posing complex ethical questions for public policy.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] There may be some leakage of the electrons transferred in the respiratory chain to form reactive oxygen species.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This was thought to result in significant oxidative stress in the mitochondria with high mutation rates of mitochondrial DNA.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Hypothesized links between aging and oxidative stress are not new and were proposed in 1956, which was later refined into the mitochondrial free radical theory of aging.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] A vicious cycle was thought to occur, as oxidative stress leads to mitochondrial DNA mutations, which can lead to enzymatic abnormalities and further oxidative stress.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] A number of changes can occur to mitochondria during the aging process.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Tissues from the skeletal muscle of elderly humans and from the brains of aged nonhuman primates show a decrease in enzymatic activity of the proteins of the respiratory chain.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] However, mutated mtDNA can only be found in about 0.2% of very old cells.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Large deletions in the mitochondrial genome have been hypothesized to lead to high levels of oxidative stress and neuronal death in Parkinson's disease.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Mitochondrial dysfunction has also been shown to occur in amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Since mitochondria cover a pivotal role in the ovarian function, by providing ATP necessary for the development from germinal vesicle to mature oocyte, a decreased mitochondria function can lead to inflammation, resulting in premature ovarian failure and accelerated ovarian aging.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The first observations of intracellular structures that probably represented mitochondria were published in 1857, by the physiologist Albert von Kolliker.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Richard Altmann, in 1890, established them as cell organelles and called them "bioblasts".
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In 1898, Carl Benda coined the term "mitochondria" from the Greek μίτος, *mitos*, "thread", and χονδρίον, *chondrion*, "granule".
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Leonor Michaelis discovered that Janus green can be used as a supravital stain for mitochondria in 1900.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In 1904, Friedrich Meves made the first recorded observation of mitochondria in plants in cells of the white waterlily, *Nymphaea alba,* and in 1908, along with Claudius Regaud, suggested that they contain proteins and lipids.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Kingsbury, in 1912, first related them with cell respiration, but almost exclusively based on morphological observations.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In 1913, Otto Heinrich Warburg linked respiration to particles which he had obtained from extracts of guinea-pig liver and which he called "grana".
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Warburg and Heinrich Otto Wieland, who had also postulated a similar particle mechanism, disagreed on the chemical nature of the respiration.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] It was not until 1925, when David Keilin discovered cytochromes, that the respiratory chain was described.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In the following years, the mechanism behind cellular respiration was further elaborated, although its link to the mitochondria was not known.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The introduction of tissue fractionation by Albert Claude allowed mitochondria to be isolated from other cell fractions and biochemical analysis to be conducted on them alone.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In 1946, he concluded that cytochrome oxidase and other enzymes responsible for the respiratory chain were isolated to the mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Eugene Kennedy and Albert Lehninger discovered in 1948 that mitochondria are the site of oxidative phosphorylation in eukaryotes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] Over time, the fractionation method was further developed, improving the quality of the mitochondria isolated, and other elements of cell respiration were determined to occur in the mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The first high-resolution electron micrographs appeared in 1952, replacing the Janus Green stains as the preferred way to visualize mitochondria.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] This led to a more detailed analysis of the structure of the mitochondria, including confirmation that they were surrounded by a membrane.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] It also showed a second membrane inside the mitochondria that folded up in ridges dividing up the inner chamber and that the size and shape of the mitochondria varied from cell to cell.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] The popular term "powerhouse of the cell" was coined by Philip Siekevitz in 1957.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In 1967, it was discovered that mitochondria contained ribosomes.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In 1968, methods were developed for mapping the mitochondrial genes, with the genetic and physical map of yeast mitochondrial DNA completed in 1976.
[src:mitochondrion/mitochondria-p02] In November 2024, researchers from the United States have discovered that mitochondria divide into two distinct forms when cells are starved, this could help explain and describe how cancers thrive in hostile conditions.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] While all scissors largely follow the same working principle, heavy-duty scissors intended for cutting tough materials tend to be called shears instead of scissors (e.g. pruning shears and grass shears), and some larger, two-handed implements are called *trimmers* instead (e.g. hedge trimmer).
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Choosing the optimal type of scissors/shears is crucial, as otherwise it can cause unwanted damage to the target material and/or the instrument itself.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Surgical scissors, used to divide tissues and trim/reshape implants during surgical operations, have even a greater variety to deal with different anatomical and procedural circumstances.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Most scissors have a ringed handle to allow readily opening for repeated cutting, and some even have spring between the shanks to assist opening (especially for shears with straight handle).
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] While historically inexpensive, mass-produced scissors often have bare metal handles, modern scissors are often designed ergonomically with composite thermoplastic and rubber covering on handles, which are more comfortable for the hand.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The noun *scissors* is treated as a plural noun and therefore takes a plural verb (e.g., *these scissors are*).
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Alternatively, the tool is referred to by the singular phrase *a pair of scissors*.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The word *shears* is used to describe similar instruments that are larger in size and for heavier cutting.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company in Hangzhou, China, has been manufacturing scissors since 1663.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Pivoted scissors were not manufactured in large numbers until 1761, when Robert Hinchliffe of Sheffield produced the first pair of modern-day scissors made of hardened and polished cast steel.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] His major challenge was to form the bows; first, he made them solid, then drilled a hole, and then filed away metal to make this large enough to admit the user's fingers.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] This process was laborious, and apparently Hinchliffe improved upon it in order to increase production.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Hinchliffe lived in Cheney Square (now the site of Sheffield Town Hall), and set up a sign identifying himself as a "fine scissor manufacturer".
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] He achieved strong sales in London and elsewhere.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The vast majority of global scissor manufacturing takes place in China.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] As of 2019, China was responsible for 64.3% of worldwide scissors exports.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] When combined with Chinese Taipei exports, this rises to 68.3%.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company, founded in 1663, is one of the oldest continuously operating scissor manufacturers in the world.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The company was nationalized in 1958 and now employs 1500 people who annually mass-produce an estimated seven million pairs of inexpensive scissors that retail for an average of US$4 each.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] In the late 14th century, the English word "scissors" came into usage.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] It was derived from the Old French word *cisoires*, which referred to shears.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] There are several historically important scissor-producing regions in France: Haute-Marne in Nogent-en Bassigny, Châtellereault, Thiers and Rouen.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] These towns, like many other scissor-producing communities, began with sabre, sword and bayonet production, which transitioned to scissors and other blades in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Thiers, in the Puy-de-Dôme department of Auvergne, remains an important centre of scissor and cutlery production.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] It is home to both the Musée de la Coutellerie, which showcases the town's 800-year history of blade-making, as well as Coutellia, an industry tradeshow that advertises itself as one of the largest annual gatherings of artisanal blade-makers in the world.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Germany was responsible for manufacturing just under 7% of global scissors exports in 2019.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Often called "The City of Blades", Solingen, in North Rhine-Westphalia, has been a center for the manufacturing of scissors since medieval times.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] At the end of the 18th century it's estimated that there were over 300 scissorsmiths in Solingen.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] In 1995 the City of Solingen passed The Solingen Ordinance, an update to a 1930s law that decreed "Made in Solingen" stamps could only be applied to products almost entirely manufactured in the old industrial area of Solingen.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] In 2019 this applied to approximately 150 companies making high-quality blades of all kinds, including scissors.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Friedrich Herder, founded in Solingen in 1727, is one of the oldest scissors manufacturers still operating in Germany.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Premana, in Lecco Province, has its origins in ironworks and knife manufacturing beginning in the 16th century.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] In 1900 there were ten scissor manufacturing workshops, 20 in 1952 and 48 by 1960.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Today, Consorzio Premax, an industrial partnership, organizes over 60 local companies involved in the manufacture of scissors for global markets.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] In 2019 Italy exported 3.5% of scissors manufactured globally.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] One of the oldest Premanese scissor manufacturing firms still in operation is Sanelli Ambrogio, which was founded in 1869.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Scissormaking in Japan evolved from sword making in the 14th century.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Seki, in Gifu Prefecture, was a renowned center of swordmaking beginning in the 1200s.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] After citizens were no longer permitted to carry swords, the city's blacksmiths turned to making scissors and knives.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] There are many specialized types of Japanese scissors, but sewing scissors were introduced by American Commodore Matthew Perry from the United States in 1854.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The Sasuke workshop in Sakai City south of Osaka is run by Yasuhiro Hirakawa, a 5th generation scissorsmith.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The company has been in operation since 1867.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Yasuhiro Hirakawa is the last traditional scissormaker in Japan, making scissors in the traditional style where the blades are believed to be thinner, lighter and sharper than European scissors.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] In 2018 he was profiled in a documentary that featured a pair of his bonsai snips which retailed for US$35,000.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] In Solsona, Spain, scissor manufacturing began in the 16th century.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] At the industry's peak in the 18th century there were 24 workshops, organized as the Guild of Saint Eligius, the patron saint of knife makers.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] By the mid-1980s there were only two, and by 2021, Pallarès Solsona, founded in 1917 by Lluìs and Carles Pallarès Canal, and still family-operated, was the town's sole remaining artisanal scissor manufacturer.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Sheffield was home to the first mass production of scissors beginning in 1761.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] By the 19th century there were an estimated 60 steel scissor companies in Sheffield.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] However, since the 1980s, industry globalization and a shift towards cheaper, mass-produced scissors created price deflation that many artisanal manufacturers could not compete with.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The Sheffield scissor industry consisted of just two local companies in 2021.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The two remaining Sheffield scissor manufacturers are William Whiteley, founded in 1760, and Ernest Wright, which was established in 1902.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Both now focus on high-end/niche crafting of "products for life" rather than mass production.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Between these two firms it is estimated that there are no more than ten "putter-togetherers" or "putters" who are the master-trained craftspeople responsible for high quality Sheffield scissor assembly.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] In 2020, Ernest Wright was recognized with the Award for Endangered Crafts by the British Heritage Crafts Association.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] There are two varieties of left-handed scissors.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Many common left-handed scissors (often called "semi"-left-handed scissors) simply have reversed finger grips.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] The blades open and close as with right-handed scissors, so that users tend to pull the blades apart as they are cutting.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] This can be challenging for craftspeople as the blades still obscure the cut.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] "True" left-handed scissors have both reversed finger grips and reversed blade layout, like mirror images of right-handed scissors.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] A left-handed person accustomed to using semi-left handed scissors may find using true left-handed scissors difficult at first, as they may have learned to rely heavily on the strength of their thumb to pull the blades apart vs. pushing the blades together in order to cut.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Some scissors are marketed as ambidextrous.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] These have symmetric handles so there is no distinction between the thumb and finger handles, and have very strong pivots so that the blades rotate without any lateral give.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] However, most "ambidextrous" scissors are in fact still right-handed in that the upper blade is on the right, and hence is on the outside when held in the right hand.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] Even if they cut successfully, the blade orientation will block the view of the cutting line for a left-handed person.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] True ambidextrous scissors are possible if the blades are double-edged and one handle is swung all the way around (to almost 360 degrees) so that what were the backs of the blades become the new cutting edges.
[src:mitochondrion/scissor] U.S. patent 3,978,584 was awarded for true ambidextrous scissors.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The oldest known trousers, dating to the period between the thirteenth and the tenth centuries BC, were found at the Yanghai cemetery in Turpan, Xinjiang (Tocharia), in present-day western China.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Made of wool, the trousers had straight legs and wide crotches and were likely made for horseback riding.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] A pair of trouser-like leggings dating back to 3350 and 3105 BC were found in the Austria–Italy border worn by Ötzi.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In most of Europe, trousers have been worn since ancient times and throughout the Medieval period, becoming the most common form of lower-body clothing for adult males in the modern world.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Breeches were worn instead of trousers in early modern Europe by some men in higher classes of society.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Distinctive formal trousers are traditionally worn with formal and semi-formal day attire.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Since the mid-twentieth century, trousers have increasingly been worn by women as well.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Jeans, made of denim, are a form of trousers for casual wear widely worn all over the world by people of both genders.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Shorts are often preferred in hot weather or for some sports and also often by children and adolescents.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trousers are worn on the hips or waist and are often held up by buttons, elastic, a belt, or suspenders (braces).
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Unless elastic, and especially for men, trousers usually provide a zippered or buttoned fly.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Jeans usually feature side and rear pockets with pocket openings placed slightly below the waist band.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] It is also possible for trousers to provide cargo pockets further down the legs.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Maintenance of fit is more challenging for trousers than for some other garments.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Leg-length can be adjusted with a hem, which helps to retain fit during the adolescent and early adulthood growth years.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Tailoring adjustment of girth to accommodate weight gain or weight loss is relatively limited, and otherwise serviceable trousers might need to be replaced after a significant change in body composition.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Higher-quality trousers often have extra fabric included in the centre-back seam allowance, so the waist can be let out further.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In Scotland, a type of tartan trousers traditionally worn by Highlanders as an alternative to the Great Plaid and its predecessors is called *trews* or in the original Gaelic *triubhas*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] This is the source of the English word *trousers*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trews are still sometimes worn instead of the kilt at ceilidhs, weddings etc.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trousers are also known as *breeks* in Scots, the cognate of *breeches*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The item of clothing worn under trousers is called *pants*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The standard English form *trousers* is also used, but it is sometimes pronounced in a manner approximately represented by [ˈtruːzɨrz], as Scots did not completely undergo the Great Vowel Shift, and thus retains the vowel sound of the Gaelic *triubhas*, from which the word originates.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In North America, Australia, and South Africa, *pants* is the general category term, whereas *trousers* (sometimes *slacks* in Australia and North America) often refers more specifically to tailored garments with a waistband, belt-loops, and a fly-front.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In these dialects, elastic-waist knitted garments would be called *pants*, but not *trousers* (or *slacks*).
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] North Americans call undergarments *underwear*, *underpants*, *undies*, or *panties* (the last are women's garments specifically) to differentiate them from other pants that are worn on the outside.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The term *drawers* normally refers to undergarments, but in some dialects, may be found as a synonym for *breeches*, that is, trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In these dialects, the term *underdrawers* is used for undergarments.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Many North Americans refer to their underpants by their type, such as *boxers* or *briefs*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In Australia, men's underwear also has various informal terms including *under-dacks*, *undies*, *dacks* or *jocks*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In New Zealand, men's underwear is known informally as *undies* or *dacks*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In India, underwear is also referred to as *innerwear*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The words *trouser* (or *pant*) instead of *trousers* (or *pants*) is sometimes used in the tailoring and fashion industries as a generic term, for instance when discussing styles, such as "a flared trouser", rather than as a specific item.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The words *trousers* and *pants* are *pluralia tantum*, nouns that generally only appear in plural form—much like the words *scissors* and *tongs*, and as such *pair of trousers* is the usual correct form.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] However, the singular form is used in some compound words, such as *trouser-leg*, *trouser-press* and *trouser-bottoms*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Jeans are trousers typically made from denim or dungaree cloth.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] There are several different main types of pants and trousers, such as dress pants, jeans, khakis, chinos, leggings, overalls, and sweatpants.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] They can also be classified by fit, fabric, and other features.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] There is apparently no universal, overarching classification.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] There is some evidence, from figurative art, of trousers being worn in the Upper Paleolithic, as seen on the figurines found at the Siberian sites of Mal'ta and Buret'.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Fabrics and technology for their construction are fragile and disintegrate easily, so often are not among artefacts discovered in archaeological sites.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Remnants of short and long trousers remain from the mummified human remains in salt mines in Iran dating back to the Persian Empire.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trousers enter recorded history in the sixth century BC, on the rock carvings and artworks of Persepolis, and with the appearance of horse-riding Eurasian nomads in Greek ethnography.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] At this time, Iranian peoples such as Scythians, Sarmatians, Sogdians and Bactrians among others, along with Armenians and Eastern and Central Asian peoples such as the Xiongnu/Hunnu, are known to have worn trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trousers are believed to have been worn by people of any gender among these early users.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The ancient Greeks used the term ἀναξυρίδες (*anaxyrides*) for the trousers worn by Eastern nations and σαράβαρα (*sarabara*) for the loose trousers worn by the Scythians.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] However, they did not wear trousers since they thought them ridiculous, using the word θύλακοι (*thulakoi*), pl. of θύλακος (*thulakos*) 'sack', as a slang term for the loose trousers of Persians and other Middle Easterners.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Republican Rome viewed the draped clothing of Greek and Minoan (Cretan) culture as an emblem of civilization and disdained trousers as the mark of barbarians.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] As the Roman Empire expanded beyond the Mediterranean basin, however, the greater warmth provided by trousers led to their adoption.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Two types of trousers eventually saw widespread use in Rome: the *feminalia*, which fit snugly and usually fell to knee length or mid-calf length, and the *braccae*, loose-fitting trousers that were closed at the ankles.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Both garments were adopted originally from the Celts of Europe, although later familiarity with the Persian Near East and the Germanic peoples increased acceptance.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] *Feminalia* and *braccae* both began use as military garments, spreading to civilian dress later, and were eventually made in a variety of materials, including leather, wool, cotton and silk.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trousers of various designs were worn throughout the Middle Ages in Europe, especially by men.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trousers in this period, generally called *braies*, varied in length and were often closed at the cuff or even had attached foot coverings, although open-legged pants were also seen.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] By the eighth century there is evidence of the wearing in Europe of two layers of trousers, especially among upper-class males.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The under layer is today referred to by costume historians as *drawers*, although that usage did not emerge until the late sixteenth century.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Over the drawers were worn trousers of wool or linen, which in the tenth century began to be referred to as *breeches* in many places.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Tightness of fit and length of leg varied by period, class, and geography.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] As undergarments, these trousers became briefer or longer as the length of the various medieval outer garments changed, and were met by, and usually attached to, another garment variously called hose or stockings.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In the fourteenth century it became common among the men of the noble and knightly classes to connect the hose directly to their pourpoints (the padded under jacket worn with armoured breastplates that would later evolve into the doublet) rather than to their drawers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In the fifteenth century, rising hemlines led to ever briefer drawers until they were dispensed with altogether by the most fashionable elites who joined their skin-tight hose back into trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] These trousers, which we would today call tights but which were still called hose or sometimes joined hose at the time, emerged late in the fifteenth century and were conspicuous by their open crotch which was covered by an independently fastening front panel, the codpiece.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The exposure of the hose to the waist was consistent with fifteenth-century trends, which also brought the pourpoint/doublet and the shirt, previously undergarments, into view, but the most revealing of these fashions were only ever adopted at court and not by the general population.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Men's clothes in Hungary in the fifteenth century consisted of a shirt and trousers as underwear, and a dolman worn over them, as well as a short fur-lined or sheepskin coat.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Hungarians generally wore simple trousers, only their colour being unusual; the dolman covered the greater part of the trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Around the turn of the sixteenth century it became conventional to separate hose into two pieces, one from the waist to the crotch which fastened around the top of the legs, called trunk hose, and the other running beneath it to the foot.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The trunk hose soon reached down the thigh to fasten below the knee and were now usually called "breeches" to distinguish them from the lower-leg coverings still called *hose* or, sometimes *stockings*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] By the end of the sixteenth century, the codpiece had also been incorporated into breeches which featured a *fly* or *fall front* opening.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] As a modernization measure, Tsar Peter the Great of Russia issued a decree in 1701 commanding every Russian man, other than clergy and peasant farmers, to wear trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] During the French Revolution of 1789 and following, many male citizens of France adopted a working-class costume including ankle-length trousers, or pantaloons (named from a Commedia dell'Arte character named *Pantalone*) in place of the aristocratic knee-breeches (*culottes*).
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Pantaloons became fashionable in early nineteenth-century England and the Regency era.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The style was introduced by Beau Brummell (1778–1840) and by mid-century had supplanted breeches as fashionable street-wear.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] At this point, even knee-length pants adopted the open bottoms of trousers (see shorts) and were worn by young boys, for sports, and in tropical climates.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Breeches proper have survived into the twenty-first century as court dress, and also in baggy mid-calf (or three-quarter length) versions known as plus-fours or knickers worn for active sports and by young schoolboys.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Types of breeches are also still worn today by fencers, baseball and American football players, and by equestrians.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Sailors may have played a role in the worldwide dissemination of trousers as a fashion.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, sailors wore baggy trousers known as *galligaskins*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Sailors also pioneered the wearing of jeans – trousers made of denim.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] These became more popular in the late nineteenth century in the American West because of their ruggedness and durability.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Starting around the mid-nineteenth century, Wigan pit-brow women scandalized Victorian society by wearing trousers for their work at the local coal mines.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] They wore skirts over their trousers and rolled them up to their waists to keep them out of the way.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Although pit-brow lasses worked above ground at the pit-head, their task of sorting and shovelling coal involved hard manual labour, so wearing the usual long skirts of the time would have greatly hindered their movements.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The Korean word for trousers, *baji* (originally *pajibaji*) first appears in recorded history around the turn of the fifteenth century, but pants may have been in use by Korean society for some time.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] From at least this time pants were worn by both sexes in Korea.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Men wore trousers either as outer garments or beneath skirts, while it was unusual for adult women to wear their pants (termed *sokgot*) without a covering skirt.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] As in Europe, a wide variety of styles came to define regions, time periods and age and gender groups, from the unlined *gouei* to the padded *sombaji*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In Western society, it was Eastern culture that inspired French designer Paul Poiret (1879–1944) to be one of the first to design pants for women.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 1913, Poiret created loose-fitting, wide-leg trousers for women called harem pants, which were based on the costumes of the popular ballet *Sheherazade*.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Written by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov in 1888, Sheherazade was based on a collection of legends from the Middle East called 1001 Arabian Nights.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In the early twentieth century, women air pilots and other working women often wore trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Frequent photographs from the 1930s of actresses Marlene Dietrich and Katharine Hepburn in trousers helped make trousers acceptable for women.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] During World War II, women employed in factories or doing other "men's work" on war service wore trousers when the job demanded it.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In the post-war era, trousers became acceptable casual wear for gardening, the beach, and other leisure pursuits.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In Britain during World War II the rationing of clothing prompted women to wear their husbands' civilian clothes, including trousers, to work while the men were serving in the armed forces.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] This was partly because they were seen as practical for work, but also so that women could keep their clothing allowance for other uses.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] As this practice of wearing trousers became more widespread and as the men's clothing wore out, replacements were needed.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] By the summer of 1944, it was reported that sales of women's trousers were five times more than the previous year.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 1919, Luisa Capetillo challenged mainstream society by becoming the first woman in Puerto Rico to wear trousers in public.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Capetillo was sent to jail for what was considered to be a crime, but the charges were later dropped.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In the 1960s, André Courrèges introduced long trousers for women as a fashion item, leading to the era of the pantsuit and designer jeans and the gradual erosion of social prohibitions against girls and women wearing trousers in schools, the workplace and in fine restaurants.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Charlotte Reid (R-Ill.) became the first woman to wear trousers in the US Congress.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Pat Nixon was the first American First Lady to wear trousers in public.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 1989, California state senator Rebecca Morgan became the first woman to wear trousers in a US state senate.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Hillary Clinton was the first woman to wear trousers in an official American First Lady portrait.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Women were not allowed to wear trousers on the US Senate floor until 1993.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In Malawi women were not legally allowed to wear trousers under President Kamuzu Banda's rule until 1994.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Since 2004 the International Skating Union has allowed women to wear trousers instead of skirts in ice-skating competitions.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2009, journalist Lubna Hussein was fined the equivalent of $200 when a court found her guilty of violating Sudan's decency laws by wearing trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2012 the Royal Canadian Mounted Police began to allow women to wear trousers and boots with all their formal uniforms.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2012 and 2013, some Mormon women participated in "Wear Pants to Church Day", in which they wore trousers to church instead of the customary dresses to encourage gender equality within the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] More than one thousand women participated in 2012.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2013, Turkey's parliament ended a ban on women lawmakers wearing trousers in its assembly.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The bylaw was originally intended to prevent women from wearing the pantalons fashionable with Parisian rebels in the French Revolution.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2014, an Indian family court in Mumbai ruled that a husband objecting to his wife wearing a kurta and jeans and forcing her to wear a sari amounts to cruelty inflicted by the husband and can be a ground to seek divorce.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The wife was thus granted a divorce on the ground of cruelty as defined under section 27(1)(d) of the Special Marriage Act, 1954.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Until 2016 some female crew members on British Airways were required to wear British Airways' standard "ambassador" uniform, which has not traditionally included trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2017, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints announced that its female employees could wear "professional pantsuits and dress slacks" while at work; dresses and skirts had previously been required.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2018 it was announced that female missionaries of that church could wear dress slacks except when attending the temple and during Sunday worship services, baptismal services, and mission leadership and zone conferences.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2019, Virgin Atlantic began to allow its female flight attendants to wear trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Pleats located just below the waistband on the front typify many styles of formal and casual trousers, including suit trousers and khakis.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] There may be one, two, three, or no pleats, which may face either direction.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] When the pleats open toward the pockets they are called reverse pleats (typical of most trousers today) and when they open toward the fly they are known as forward pleats.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In modern trousers, men's models generally have pockets for carrying small items such as wallets, keys or mobile phones, but women's trousers often do not – and sometimes have what are called Potemkin pockets, a fake slit sewn shut.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] If there are pockets, they are often much smaller than in men's clothes.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2018, journalists at The Pudding found less than half of women's front pockets could fit a thin wallet, let alone a handheld phone and keys.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trouser-makers can finish the legs by hemming the bottom to prevent fraying.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trousers with turn-ups (cuffs in American English), after hemming, are rolled outward and sometimes pressed or stitched into place.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] A fly is a covering over an opening join concealing the mechanism, such as a zipper, velcro, or buttons, used to join the opening.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In trousers, this is most commonly an opening covering the groin, which makes the pants easier to put on or take off.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The opening also allows men to urinate without lowering their trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Trousers have varied historically in whether or not they have a fly.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Originally, hose did not cover the area between the legs.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] This was instead covered by a doublet or by a codpiece.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] When breeches were worn, during the Regency period for example, they were fall-fronted (or broad fall).
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Later, after trousers (pantaloons) were invented, the fly-front (split fall) emerged.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The panelled front returned as a sporting option, such as in riding breeches, but is now hardly ever used, a fly being by far the most common fastening.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Most flies now use a zipper, though button-fly pants continue to be available.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] At present, most trousers are held up through the assistance of a belt which is passed through the **belt loops** on the waistband of the trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] However, this was traditionally a style acceptable only for casual trousers and work trousers; suit trousers and formal trousers were suspended by the use of braces (*suspenders* in American English) attached to buttons located on the interior or exterior of the waistband.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Today, this remains the preferred method of trouser support amongst adherents of classical British tailoring.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Many men claim this method is more effective and more comfortable because it requires no cinching of the waist or periodic adjustment.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In modern Western society, males customarily wear trousers and not skirts or dresses.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] There are exceptions, however, such as the ceremonial Scottish kilt and Greek fustanella, as well as robes or robe-like clothing such as the cassocks of clergy and the academic robes, both rarely worn today in daily use.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Among certain groups, low-rise, baggy trousers exposing underwear became fashionable; for example, among skaters and in 1990s hip hop fashion.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] This fashion is called sagging or, alternatively, "busting slack".
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] These groups permit women to wear underpants as long as they are hidden.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] By contrast, many Muslim sects approve of pants as they are considered more modest than any skirt that is shorter than ankle length.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] However, some mosques require ankle length trousers for both Muslims and non-Muslims on the premises.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The Catholic Pope Nicholas I approved of both men and women wearing pants.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The wife was thus granted a divorce on the ground of cruelty as defined under section 27(1)(d) of Special Marriage Act, 1954.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In Rome in 1992, a 45-year-old driving instructor was accused of rape.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] When he picked up an 18-year-old for her first driving lesson, he allegedly raped her for an hour, then told her that if she was to tell anyone he would kill her.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Later that night she told her parents and her parents agreed to help her press charges.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] While the alleged rapist was convicted and sentenced, the Supreme Court of Cassation overturned the conviction in 1998 because the victim wore tight jeans.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] It was argued that she must have necessarily have had to help her attacker remove her jeans, thus making the act consensual ("because the victim wore very, very tight jeans, she had to help him remove them...and by removing the jeans...it was no longer rape but consensual sex").
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The court stated in its decision "it is a fact of common experience that it is nearly impossible to slip off tight jeans even partly without the active collaboration of the person who is wearing them." This ruling sparked widespread feminist protest.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] The day after the decision, women in the Italian Parliament protested by wearing jeans and holding placards that read "Jeans: An Alibi for Rape".
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] As a sign of support, the California Senate and Assembly followed suit.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Soon Patricia Giggans, executive director of the Los Angeles Commission on Assaults Against Women, (now Peace Over Violence) made Denim Day an annual event.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] As of 2011 at least 20 U.S. states officially recognize Denim Day in April.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Wearing jeans on this day, 22 April, has become an international symbol of protest.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In 2008 the Supreme Court of Cassation overturned the ruling, so there is no longer a "denim" defense to the charge of rape.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In Malawi, women were not legally allowed to wear trousers under President Kamuzu Banda's rule until 1994.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Capetillo was sent to jail for what was then considered to be a crime, but the judge later dropped the charges against her.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In Sudan, Article 152 of the Memorandum to the 1991 Penal Code prohibits the wearing of "obscene outfits" in public.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] This law has been used to arrest and prosecute women wearing trousers.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Thirteen women including journalist Lubna al-Hussein were arrested in Khartoum in July 2009 for wearing trousers; ten of the women pleaded guilty and were flogged with ten lashes and fined 250 Sudanese pounds apiece.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Lubna al-Hussein considers herself a good Muslim and asserts "Islam does not say whether a woman can wear trousers or not.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] But it is insulting." She was eventually found guilty and fined the equivalent of $200 rather than being flogged.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In May 2004, in Louisiana, Democrat and state legislator Derrick Shepherd proposed a bill that would make it a crime to appear in public wearing trousers below the waist and thereby exposing one's skin or "intimate clothing".
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In February 2005, Virginia legislators tried to pass a similar law that would have made punishable by a $50 fine "any person who, while in a public place, intentionally wears and displays his below-waist undergarments, intended to cover a person's intimate parts, in a lewd or indecent manner".
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] (It is not clear whether, with the same coverage by the trousers, exposing underwear was considered worse than exposing bare skin, or whether the latter was already covered by another law.) The law passed in the Virginia House of Delegates.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] However, various criticisms to it arose.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] For example, newspaper columnists and radio talk show hosts consistently said that since most people that would be penalized under the law would be young African-American men, the law would thus be a form of racial discrimination.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Virginia's state senators voted against passing the law.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] In California, Government Code Section 12947.5 (part of the California Fair Employment and Housing Act (FEHA)) expressly protects the right to wear pants.
[src:mitochondrion/trouser] Thus, the standard California FEHA discrimination complaint form includes an option for "denied the right to wear pants".
